Excellent. Perfect taste and texture for a belgian waffle. Tried using smart balance so I wouldn't feel so bad about eating all that butter and it still turns out great.

Rating: 4
I really messed with this (not all on purpose) and they came out CRISPY! I doubled the recipe but forgot to add the butter! Added only 5 tbs total(with a dash of vanilla) at the end and they still came out great. To give them a bit of a nutritional boost I threw in a heaping 1/4 cup of wheat germ and a dash of milk to make up for the additional dry ingredient. Didn't serve Prosciutto. Yes, Bisquick might be easier but it has ingredients that are not so great...I am going to add a bit of Oat Bran to the next batch for some fiber!

Rating: 4
EXCELLENT. used a standard 4-waffle iron and skipped the meat, as was making for kids. had to guess a little at how much batter for my waffle iron  for those of you with the standard 4-waffle kind, a double recipe of this makes 3 irons full (or 12 individual waffles), so a single would make 1.5 irons/ 6 waffles.

Rating: 3
This is a good (but not great) basic waffle recipe. The waffles are light, not dense. I reduced the butter to 3 tablespoons with no issue and put crumbled cooked bacon into the batter rather than prosciutto on the side. It was well-received by my family, but is nothing outstanding.

