I love this recipe! Very tasty.

Rating: 3
This was a good recipe. At first, I didn't think it would taste very good, but it turned out quite delicious. I added vanilla to the batter to give it more of a punch and the addition worked out well.

Rating: 3
My husband and son are waffle hounds, so I have tried many recipes, but this is the best. The texture is light and not at all rubbery, unlike some other recipes. Also, there is no taste of leavening agents. The recipe works well in my ski house, where the altitude (4,000 feet) often causes batters to rise too far, too fast. It doubles easily, which is important in my house, especially since the recipe makes a scant two servings, with no spare batter to use if I burn a waffle or miscalculate the amount of batter needed and have to throw one out. The prosciutto is not at all important.

Rating: 2
Not much different than bisquick? The waffles came out good and were enjoyed by all who tried them. There wasn't much of a buttermilk flavor though and for the amount of work there wasn't any noticeable differnce between this scratch version and Bisquick waffles. Prosciutto was nice but not really worth getting another pan dirty.

Rating: 4
Wonderful! The recipe is perfect to serve two. We both liked the slight outside crispness, leading to a nice inside texture. The batter looks like tapioca pudding, but is a great consistency for the waffle iron. I am looking for excuses to make these again - despite the calories found in waffles.

